+      "passageText": "Passage\nAt the heart of agroecology is the idea that agroecosystems should\nmimic the biodiversity levels and functioning of natural ecosystems.\nSuch agricultural mimics, like their natural models, can be productive,\npest-resistant, nutrient conserving, and resilient to shocks and stresses.\nIn ecosystems there is no ‘waste’ , nutrients are recycled indefinitely.\nAgroecology aims at closing nutrient loops, i.e., returning all nutrients\nthat come out of the soil back to the soil such as through application of\nfarmyard manure. It also harnesses natural processes to control pests and\nbuild soil fertility i.e., through intercropping. Agroecological practices\ninclude integrating trees with livestock and crops.",
